<article>
    <h1>Proof of the (mud) pud&#xAD;ding</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200919/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-19"><time>2020-09-19</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | MOTORING</span>
        - <span role="byline">Chong Jun Liang</span>
    </section>

    <p>Be­ing a motoring en­thu­si­ast, I re­ceived the as­sign­ment to pho­to­graph the Jeep Gla­di­a­tor with glee. Af­ter all, how of­ten does one get to ex­pe­ri­ence Jeep’s famed off-road­ing ca­pa­bil­i­ties in our con­crete jun­gle?</p>
    <p>I drove to a forested area in cen­tral Sin­ga­pore and made a cau­tious start by en­gag­ing the Gla­di­a­tor’s 4H (four-wheel-drive high range) Auto mode via a ded­i­cated shift lever next to the main trans­mis­sion lever. It is a fool­proof mode which al­lows the Jeep to de­cide whether to use rear-wheel- or four-wheel-drive.</p>
    <p>Af­ter some easy driv­ing on a flat grass patch, I got more ad­ven­tur­ous and slowly climbed a steep slope. At this point, I se­lected the 4L (four-wheel-drive low range) mode. This pro­vided more trac­tion and torque to the front and rear axles evenly.</p>
    <p>This proved to be wise as it stormed the night be­fore and the grassy slope was slick and muddy. A front wheel sank into the soft ground and the Jeep tilted to one side. Lesser ve­hi­cles might have suc­cumbed, but the Gla­di­a­tor sim­ply shrugged and trudged on.</p>
    <p>Its pli­ant dampers ab­sorbed the bumps eas­ily, pro­vid­ing a sta­ble and com­fort­able ride with­out spoil­ing the fun.</p>
    <p>With new­found con­fi­dence, I de­scended with vigour and drove through the for­est with swag­ger.</p>
    <p>I com­pleted my short off-road­ing ex­pe­di­tion by cut­ting through a large wa­ter pud­dle be­fore get­ting back onto the paved road.</p>


